				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">Due to work and stuff, I did manage to find some time to experiment a bit with the PPU clone I have, UA6528. With the PIC18F4221, I built the circuit, connecting the /CS, D0-D7 and A0-A2 from the PPU to the microcontroller to test the output. I've also verified the output with an oscilloscope, NTSC signals are correct from the &quot;Video Out&quot; pin.<br /><br />Using the oscillator-in-can (4-pin) ones (21.42MHz) and with the NTSC version of the PPU, I managed to coax it to display an entire background of a red, green or blue (intensify one color only) through one of the PPU registers. I got those hints from the &quot;NerdyNights&quot; first app tutorial (thanks to the author). <br /><br />I have not connected the memory yet (that is the hardest part, to be honest) and I may be putting these up slowly. I will put some pictures of the PPU output captured from my TV framegrabber, since I do not have an accessible CRT nearby my table. <img src="./images/smilies/icon_smile.gif" alt=":)" title="Smile" /><br /><br />Actually, prior to all that idea, someone from Japan has made up a mini game using an AVR and the official NES' PPU, RP2C02, with another commonly used arcade sound chip: <a href="http://www.geocities.jp/r8ctiny/avrrp2/avrrp2.html" class="postlink">http://www.geocities.jp/r8ctiny/avrrp2/avrrp2.html</a></div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

